{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568685"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.01,0.08,0.23,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89634"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"6555"},{"type":"tags","id":"6556"},{"type":"tags","id":"6571"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a two-hour history of sudden onset, tearing chest pain, worse between the shoulder blades. His history includes hypertension for which he takes perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he looks unwell with a blood pressure of 160/100mmHg, pulse rate of 90/min and temperature 37.2C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. He is given oxygen by face mask and an ECG is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT coronary angiogram","MR coronary angiogram","Percutaneous coronary angiography","Transthoracic echocardiogram","CT angiography chest and abdomen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute, severe, tearing chest pain radiating to the back, which is highly suggestive of aortic dissection, especially in the context of hypertension. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography chest and abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it is rapid, widely available, and provides detailed information about the aorta and its branches, allowing for prompt diagnosis and surgical planning. It is considered the gold standard for diagnosing aortic dissection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT coronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to assess the coronary arteries for atherosclerotic disease and is not suitable for diagnosing aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMR coronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used in the acute setting due to limited availability, longer scan times, and the need for patient stability, making it less appropriate in this emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous coronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure used to assess for acute coronary syndromes, but does not visualise the aorta and would not diagnose aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E can sometimes detect proximal aortic dissection but is less sensitive than CT angiography, especially for distal dissections, and may miss important findings in the chest and abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERapid identification and management of aortic dissection are essential, as delays can be fatal. CT angiography is the gold standard in most emergency settings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute, severe, tearing chest pain radiating to the back in a person with hypertension is highly suggestive of aortic dissection.","CT angiography of the chest and abdomen is the investigation of choice for suspected aortic dissection due to its speed and accuracy.","Prompt diagnosis and management of aortic dissection are critical to reduce morbidity and mortality."],"references":["Briggs B, Cline D. Diagnosing aortic dissection: A review of this elusive, lethal diagnosis. J Am Coll Emerg Physicians Open. 2024 Jul 8;5(4):e13225. doi: 10.1002/emp2.13225"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21871"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21871"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/HCGh3FOlzGDyB5ba7Cqh4akGLMrJ8f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/HCGh3FOlzGDyB5ba7Cqh4akGLMrJ8f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1026,"height":552}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89634"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T21:34:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:35:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107179"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA